sec.p:
We manipulated perceived predation levels (PPLs) during spring and summer (March through July) among 12 nest box plots of great tits over a 2-year period (Fig. 1a). As a low-PPL treatment, we broadcast songs of a bird species, the common blackbird (Turdus merula), which is neither a predator nor a competitor of great tits. As a high-PPL treatment, we broadcast calls of the European sparrowhawk. Our playback frequency matched natural vocalization frequencies, and we broadcast on a 4 day on 4-day off scheme to avoid habituation10. Our playback design may have also altered individuals’ perception of temporal variance in risk, another factor influencing anti-predator behavior13, although competing theories debate whether mean rather than variance is important for prey to interpret predator cues14. Birds decreased risky communication behaviors (detailed above) in the high-PPL treatment but actual predator numbers were not affected (based on weekly counts)15, verifying that our manipulations influenced perceived—not actual—predation levels. In this vein, our aim with this study is to determine how behavioral types differ in their adjustment of reproductive investment in response to perceived levels.Fig. 1
