Path analyses revealed alternative behavioral strategies, related to exploratory tendency, individual plasticity in timing of breeding in response to PPL, and consequently, the existence of repeatable individual variation in timing of breeding within each PPL treatment (Fig. 3). Under low PPL, fast explorers initiated their clutches later than slow explorers (βexploration → lay date ± SE: 0.32 ± 0.06, z = 5.46, P < 0.001, n = 172, Fig. 2b), which negatively affected their clutch size because later breeders produced smaller clutches (βlay date→ clutch size ± SE: −0.53 ± 0.05, z = −9.59, P < 0.001, n = 172). However, among birds sharing the same lay date, faster explorers produced larger clutches (βexploration → clutch size ± SE: 0.37 ± 0.05, z = 6.70, P < 0.001, n = 172). Importantly, the positive direct effect of exploratory behavior on clutch size canceled out the negative indirect effect on clutch size caused by faster explorers breeding late: the overall among-individual correlation between exploratory behavior and clutch size (Supplementary Table 4) was consequently close to 0 (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
