We used bivariate mixed-effects models to estimate the pattern of among-individual variation in plasticity in response to PPL treatment for each of the three phenotypic traits (lay date, clutch size, exploratory behavior; defined above) separately (Supplementary Tables 1, 2). Each bivariate mixed-effects model fitted the focal trait expressed in the low-PPL versus high-PPL treatment as two separate response variables (e.g., lay date expressed in the low-PPL treatment, and lay date expressed in the high-PPL treatment). The intercept values of the two response variables represented the treatment-specific mean values, and no further fixed effects were thus included (except for analyses of exploratory behavior fitting sex and time of day as fixed effects, see above). Random intercepts were included for PlotYear and individual identity (as above). These bivariate analyses thus partitioned the total phenotypic variance not attributable to fixed effects (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
